## Study of Computation

For other uses, see [Computer science (disambiguation)](/Computer_science_(disambiguation)).

This is where we dissect the very essence of what it means to process information, to automate tasks, to understand the limits of the possible. It's not just about the blinking lights and humming servers; it's about the underlying principles, the abstract machinery that makes it all tick.

### Fundamental Areas of Computer Science

Before we dive into the abyss, let's acknowledge the pillars upon which this whole endeavor rests. These are the territories that define the landscape:

*   [Programming Language Theory](/Programming_language_theory): The art and science of how we tell machines what to do, and the fundamental properties of those languages.
*   [Computer Architecture](/Computer_architecture): The blueprint of the machine itself, how its components are structured and interact.
*   [Artificial Intelligence](/Artificial_intelligence): The ambitious, often overhyped, pursuit of creating intelligence in machines.
*   [Computational Complexity Theory](/Computational_complexity_theory): The study of the resources required to solve problems, and the inherent difficulty of those problems.

And then there's the overarching field itself, [Computer science](/Computer_science), with its own labyrinthine [History](/History_of_computer_science), its comprehensive [Outline](/Outline_of_computer_science), and its own specialized [Glossary](/Glossary_of_computer_science). It all falls under the umbrella of [Category:Computer science](/Category:Computer_science), naturally.

### The Core of the Matter

Computer science, at its heart, is the rigorous examination of [computation](/Computation), the abstract nature of [information](/Information), and the mechanisms of [automation](/Automation). &#91;1&#93; &#91;2&#93; &#91;3&#93; It's a field that straddles the line between pure [sciences](/Science) and applied disciplines. On one side, you have the [theoretical disciplines](/Theoretical_computer_science), delving into the elegance of [algorithms](/Algorithm), the foundational [theory of computation](/Theory_of_computation), and the quantifiable limits of [information theory](/Information_theory). On the other, you have the [applied disciplines](/Applied_science), focused on the tangible: the intricate design and meticulous implementation of [hardware](/Computer_architecture) and the sprawling world of [software](/Software_engineering). &#91;4&#93; &#91;5&#93; &#91;6&#93; The individuals who navigate this intricate domain are known, rather grandly, as [computer scientists](/Computer_scientist).

At the very core of this discipline lie algorithms and [data structures](/Data_structure). They are the building blocks, the fundamental tools that any serious practitioner must master. &#91;7&#93; The theory of computation, a particularly abstract corner of this field, grapples with the fundamental nature of [models of computation](/Models_of_computation) and the inherent capabilities and limitations of these abstract machines when tackling various [problems](/Computational_problem). Within this theoretical framework, fields like [cryptography](/Cryptography) and [computer security](/Computer_security) emerge, dedicated to the art of secure communication and the relentless battle against [security vulnerabilities](/Security_vulnerabilities). Further afield, [computer graphics](/Computer_graphics_(computer_science)) and [computational geometry](/Computational_geometry) explore the creation and manipulation of visual information. The intricate world of [programming language theory](/Programming_language_theory) dissects the myriad ways we can express computational processes, while [database](/Database) theory focuses on the systematic management of vast repositories of data. The interface between humans and machines is the domain of [human–computer interaction](/Human%E2%80%93computer_interaction), a field that seeks to understand and improve this crucial relationship. Meanwhile, [software engineering](/Software_engineering) concerns itself with the principles and practices behind building robust and maintainable software. Systems themselves, from the foundational [operating systems](/Operating_system) and sprawling [computer networks](/Computer_network) to the embedded intricacies of [embedded systems](/Embedded_system), are subject to intense study, exploring the principles behind their design and operation within the context of [complex systems](/Complex_system). And, of course, [computer architecture](/Computer_architecture) lays bare the very construction of computer components and the equipment that makes them function. Finally, the ambitious fields of [artificial intelligence](/Artificial_intelligence) and [machine learning](/Machine_learning) strive to replicate or synthesize goal-oriented processes—problem-solving, decision-making, adaptation, [planning](/Automated_planning_and_scheduling), and learning—that we observe in humans and animals. Within AI, [computer vision](/Computer_vision) seeks to imbue machines with the ability to "see" and interpret visual data, while [natural language processing](/Natural_language_processing) aims to equip them with the capacity to understand and process human language.

Ultimately, the central preoccupation of computer science, the question that echoes through its halls, is this: what can, and more importantly, what *cannot* be automated? &#91;2&#93; &#91;8&#93; &#91;3&#93; &#91;9&#93; &#91;10&#93; The [Turing Award](/Turing_Award), a distinction of the highest order, is generally reserved for those who have profoundly advanced our understanding of this fundamental query. &#91;11&#93; &#91;12&#93;

